239 /**
240 @brief
241 Converts a given floating point number to a zero-terminated string
242 representation with a given field width using the 'e' format
243 (aka scientific notation) or the 'f' one.
244
245 @details
246 The format is chosen automatically to provide the most number of significant
247 digits (and thus, precision) with a given field width. In many cases, the
248 result is similar to that of sprintf(to, "%g", x) with a few notable
249 differences:
250 - the conversion is usually more precise than C library functions.
251 - there is no 'precision' argument. instead, we specify the number of
252 characters available for conversion (i.e. a field width).
253 - the result never exceeds the specified field width. If the field is too
254 short to contain even a rounded decimal representation, my_gcvt()
255 indicates overflow and truncates the output string to the specified width.
256 - float-type arguments are handled differently than double ones. For a
257 float input number (i.e. when the 'type' argument is MY_GCVT_ARG_FLOAT)
258 we deliberately limit the precision of conversion by FLT_DIG digits to
259 avoid garbage past the significant digits.
260 - unlike sprintf(), in cases where the 'e' format is preferred, we don't
261 zero-pad the exponent to save space for significant digits. The '+' sign
262 for a positive exponent does not appear for the same reason.
263
264 @param x the input floating point number.
265 @param type is either MY_GCVT_ARG_FLOAT or MY_GCVT_ARG_DOUBLE.
266 Specifies the type of the input number (see notes above).
267 @param width field width in characters. The minimal field width to
268 hold any number representation (albeit rounded) is 7
269 characters ("-Ne-NNN").
270 @param to pointer to the output buffer. The result is always
271 zero-terminated, and the longest returned string is thus
272 'width + 1' bytes.
273 @param error if not NULL, points to a location where the status of
274 conversion is stored upon return.
275 false successful conversion
276 true the input number is [-,+]infinity or nan.
277 The output string in this case is always '0'.
278 @return number of written characters (excluding terminating '\0')
279
280 @todo
281 Check if it is possible and makes sense to do our own rounding on top of
282 dtoa() instead of calling dtoa() twice in (rare) cases when the resulting
283 string representation does not fit in the specified field width and we want
284 to re-round the input number with fewer significant digits. Examples:
285
286 my_gcvt(-9e-3, ..., 4, ...);
287 my_gcvt(-9e-3, ..., 2, ...);
288 my_gcvt(1.87e-3, ..., 4, ...);
289 my_gcvt(55, ..., 1, ...);
290
291 We do our best to minimize such cases by:
292
293 - passing to dtoa() the field width as the number of significant digits
294
295 - removing the sign of the number early (and decreasing the width before
296 passing it to dtoa())
297
298 - choosing the proper format to preserve the most number of significant
299 digits.
300 */

1242 strtod for IEEE--arithmetic machines.
1243
1244 This strtod returns a nearest machine number to the input decimal
1245 string (or sets errno to EOVERFLOW). Ties are broken by the IEEE round-even
1246 rule.
1247
1248 Inspired loosely by William D. Clinger's paper "How to Read Floating
1249 Point Numbers Accurately" [Proc. ACM SIGPLAN '90, pp. 92-101].
1250
1251 Modifications:
1252
1253 1. We only require IEEE (not IEEE double-extended).
1254 2. We get by with floating-point arithmetic in a case that
1255 Clinger missed -- when we're computing d * 10^n
1256 for a small integer d and the integer n is not too

1261 result in the hard case, we use floating-point
1262 arithmetic to determine the adjustment to within
1263 one bit; only in really hard cases do we need to
1264 compute a second residual.
1265 4. Because of 3., we don't need a large table of powers of 10
1266 for ten-to-e (just some small tables, e.g. of 10^k
1267 for 0 <= k <= 22).
1268 */

1890 /*
1891 dtoa for IEEE arithmetic (dmg): convert double to ASCII string.
1892
1893 Inspired by "How to Print Floating-Point Numbers Accurately" by
1894 Guy L. Steele, Jr. and Jon L. White [Proc. ACM SIGPLAN '90, pp. 112-126].
1895
1896 Modifications:
1897 1. Rather than iterating, we use a simple numeric overestimate
1898 to determine k= floor(log10(d)). We scale relevant
1899 quantities using O(log2(k)) rather than O(k) multiplications.
1900 2. For some modes > 2 (corresponding to ecvt and fcvt), we don't
1901 try to generate digits strictly left to right. Instead, we
1902 compute with fewer bits and propagate the carry if necessary
1903 when rounding the final digit up. This is often faster.
1904 3. Under the assumption that input will be rounded nearest,
1905 mode 0 renders 1e23 as 1e23 rather than 9.999999999999999e22.
1906 That is, we allow equality in stopping tests when the
1907 round-nearest rule will give the same floating-point value
1908 as would satisfaction of the stopping test with strict
1909 inequality.
1910 4. We remove common factors of powers of 2 from relevant
1911 quantities.
1912 5. When converting floating-point integers less than 1e16,
1913 we use floating-point arithmetic rather than resorting
1914 to multiple-precision integers.
1915 6. When asked to produce fewer than 15 digits, we first try
1916 to get by with floating-point arithmetic; we resort to
1917 multiple-precision integer arithmetic only if we cannot
1918 guarantee that the floating-point calculation has given
1919 the correctly rounded result. For k requested digits and
1920 "uniformly" distributed input, the probability is
1921 something like 10^(k-15) that we must resort to the Long
1922 calculation.
1923 */
1924
1925 4879254 static char *dtoa(double dd, int mode, int ndigits, int *decpt, int *sign,
1926 char **rve, char *buf, size_t buf_size) {
1927 /*
1928 Arguments ndigits, decpt, sign are similar to those
1929 of ecvt and fcvt; trailing zeros are suppressed from
1930 the returned string. If not null, *rve is set to point
1931 to the end of the return value. If d is +-Infinity or NaN,
1932 then *decpt is set to DTOA_OVERFLOW.
1933
1934 mode:
1935 0 ==> shortest string that yields d when read in
1936 and rounded to nearest.
1937 1 ==> like 0, but with Steele & White stopping rule;
1938 e.g. with IEEE P754 arithmetic , mode 0 gives
1939 1e23 whereas mode 1 gives 9.999999999999999e22.
1940 2 ==> max(1,ndigits) significant digits. This gives a
1941 return value similar to that of ecvt, except
1942 that trailing zeros are suppressed.
1943 3 ==> through ndigits past the decimal point. This
1944 gives a return value similar to that from fcvt,
1945 except that trailing zeros are suppressed, and
1946 ndigits can be negative.
1947 4,5 ==> similar to 2 and 3, respectively, but (in
1948 round-nearest mode) with the tests of mode 0 to
1949 possibly return a shorter string that rounds to d.
1950 With IEEE arithmetic and compilation with
1951 -DHonor_FLT_ROUNDS, modes 4 and 5 behave the same
1952 as modes 2 and 3 when FLT_ROUNDS != 1.
1953 6-9 ==> Debugging modes similar to mode - 4: don't try
1954 fast floating-point estimate (if applicable).
1955
1956 Values of mode other than 0-9 are treated as mode 0.
1957
1958 Sufficient space is allocated to the return value
1959 to hold the suppressed trailing zeros.
1960 */
